Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical uniformities in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among the stars related, that is, arising from the same cluster.
The authors published the results of their research in the journal Nature, and they can be found briefly on the university’s website.
The reason for the same chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in gas clouds, preceding the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the stellar cluster, by its chemical composition it is possible to determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of relatives stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of simulations carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, the researchers used a supercomputer to simulate two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
Over a period of several million years, this object, under the influence of its own gravity, is transformed into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
The scientists added label paints to the initial gas flows and found that rapid turbulent stirring in the cloud achieves a high degree of chemical uniformity.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for stars-related by chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
