Recalling the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill that would protect trade union organization as a civil right.
“Where there are unions, there are middle-class jobs,” says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is co-chair of the Progressive Faction Congress.
That’s why I’m proud to introduce the Workers’ Empowerment Act, along with John Lewis, the symbol of the civil rights movement.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate against trade union organizations as it does against other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of union opponents.
Amendments to the Labour Relations Regulation Act to allow workers who face discrimination for participating in trade unions to seek justice in civil courts – and receive damages and penalties – are a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis, and the co-authors of the bill are proposing is to recall a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that unions have been subjected to in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans have once supported countries around the world in adopting, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time, which millions of Americans still remember, when this country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution drafted to ensure that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that read openly: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and to every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right would have no legal force; measures aimed at this end would be considered illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations as a world treaty, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect their interests.”
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic premise that labour rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize unions — and to have that union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies — must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is indeed wise to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but has increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, the trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and elevated an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers us as well.
Official recognition of labour rights as human rights – and expanding civil rights protections to prevent discrimination against trade unions – is long overdue.
Keith Allison and John Lewis are reviving the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge temporarily blocks a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana
In the US, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of a Louisiana law, which his supporters say is likely to close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed into effect by Louisiana Governor Bobby Ginadel in June and was due to take effect on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have the authority to receive patients in a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that at the moment, doctors can continue to perform legal abortions, continuing to seek such authority.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to take action to obtain authority," Judge John deGravells wrote in his ruling.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month, during which the judge will render a more permanent decision on this law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to get hospital credentials.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from the insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who had not acted as plaintiffs in the case and had also applied for admission authority.
Louisiana is part of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, and courts have recently declared such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have closed most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say admission laws impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion object that such measures are aimed at protecting women's health, although some have also noted their positive effect on the closure of clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has hospital admission authority, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while their applications for admission authority await a decision.
What will lead to the introduction of quotas on domestic products
At least half of the products for each type of goods in the range of retail chains should be Russian-made, according to a deputy of the State Duma from the faction "Fair Russia" Oleg Nilov.
The parliamentarian has prepared a bill aimed at introducing protective measures against domestic producers, writes the newspaper "Izvestia".
The document will still be detailed to avoid possible discomfort for buyers.
This applies to goods that are not produced in Russia. <...> For the rest of the groups of products that are produced in Russia, the retailer will have to provide at least half of its shelves to domestic manufacturers," Nilov said.
Along with amendments to the article “On the basics of state regulation of trade activity in the Russian Federation”, the bill provides for amendments to the Tax Code, establishing a reduced VAT rate of 10% when selling products produced in Russia.
The idea of introducing a 50% quota in trade networks is part of a package of stimulus measures for Russian manufacturers.
On the shelves will appear several times more domestic goods.
However, the initiative can have both positive and negative effects, experts say.
According to Sergey Litvinenko, a lawyer for the company “Taxpayer”, a member of the independent expert center “Public Duma”, for the Russian economy, as well as for the domestic agricultural and food industries, the effect will be positive and will lead to growth.
In the plus there will be farmers, farmers, small shops.
They will be able to sell more, which means that profits will increase.
In addition, they will get the right to dictate to retailers their terms and prices, because they will be forced to buy their goods.
Russian manufacturers will be able to increase their activities and sales, which will lead to higher taxes than before.
This will increase budget revenues, create new jobs, some industries will begin to expand, some will be mastered faster, and will contribute to GDP growth.
Russia's dependence on foreign food will decrease several times, however, not immediately," the expert notes.
Previously, Russian enterprises often could not break into the shelves of local stores due to high competition from foreign counterparts.
Now, after the embargo, this niche is freed and you can breathe a sigh of relief.
But do not forget that after all the necessary approvals and sanitary inspections, the Russian market will receive food products from Latin America, Turkey and Serbia.
In other words, now there is a "moment of calm", when the former players have already left, and the new ones have not yet arrived.
Almost a month later, we can talk about the increased demand for domestic raw materials, as well as the increase in prices for finished products," said Tamara Kasyanova, First Vice-President of the all-Russian public organization "Russian Club of Financial Directors".
Clearly, the idea of selling at least 50% of Russian food products in each category will allow to anchor the sector to local producers.
In this case, they will compete with each other, and not with goods that, at the expense of subsidies from another state, are cheaper.
In other words, the fight for the buyer will unfold between companies working under the same laws of the industry.
On the other hand, Kasyanova notes, Russian producers are able to meet 50% of the domestic needs of compatriots far from all articles.
And in this situation, retail chains will have to “catch up” the share of Russian goods to half the assortment.
In this regard, there are growing fears that low-quality goods will enter the shelves.
Perhaps, under the guise of manufactured in Russia, foreign products with broken labels will be supplied," the expert adds.
The negative effect of the introduction of quotas will be felt by large trading networks, especially those that are more profitable to cooperate with importers.
It is logical that foreign suppliers themselves will suffer from this situation, since the demand for their products will decrease.
Litvinenko does not exclude that the law on quotas for domestic goods may also affect consumers.
The fact is that some products of Russian production may be inferior in quality to imported analogues, while stores will be able to inflate prices for the latter as a scarce commodity.
The idea of import substitution, which was forgotten in the early 2000s, was revived by economists in February this year due to the ongoing devaluation of the ruble.
Now, against the backdrop of difficult relations with the West, the question of abandoning imported products is becoming even more urgent.
The law is designed to oblige retailers to take into account domestic manufacturers when forming orders for suppliers.
Then we will go much faster and more confidently on the path of import substitution, and the production planning system for the necessary types of products will be created in a shorter time," said Deputy Oleg Nilov.
The quota mechanism will be particularly effective for those agricultural sectors where the potential is particularly high, for example, in the dairy industry, where the share of imports was 25%.
Our farmers are really able to fully cover the shelves of Russian stores.
In addition, a powerful impetus can get and meat production.
As you know, the largest share of imports remains beef - from 30% to 35%.
It turns out that 65-70% are still Russian products," Kasyanova said.
Experts are of the opinion that the introduction of quotas for domestic products will contribute to import substitution and can accelerate this process.
However, in itself, this initiative will not lead to import substitution, because it requires a set of measures, Litvinenko is sure.
In any case, 50% of the goods sold under this initiative can still be brought from abroad, which means that full import substitution will not occur, but significant steps in this direction will be taken.
In addition, it is not enough to establish quotas, it is still necessary to establish the production of domestic products in the country in order to fulfill these quotas.
These quotas are just such guarantees and will provide", - the expert states.
Late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment mean that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video in memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women in rural Australia are at a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in urban areas.
Researchers analyzed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute for Medical Research reported that those living in regions and remote areas of the state were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than those living in urban areas.
SMALL RESEARCH: New drugs may slow lung cancer and ovarian cancer
The researchers followed the medical path of women for seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the woman’s age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also influenced the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those with cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the likelihood of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that a late diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities," she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of out-of-home services that would allow specialists to treat women closer to home and support programs for people receiving treatment far from home could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that long life expectancy among women with ovarian cancer was rare, emphasizing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2012, at the age of 33, a young Gold Coast mother, Elisha Niv, was told she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
