Inflation is out of vacation.
Will the Russians feel a sharp increase in prices?
As a result of cross-sanctions of the Russian Federation and the West, inflation in Russia will accelerate and will not comply with the forecasts of the authorities, analysts of VTB Capital are convinced.
According to experts, the delayed consequences of anti-sanctions will lead to inflationary shock in the first quarter of 2015, writes RBC Daily.
According to the latest forecast of the Ministry of Economic Development, in 2014 inflation will be 6.5-7.5%, next year even less - 6.5%.
However, according to Kommersant newspaper, this week the mayor should make “small but fundamental” adjustments to the macroeconomic forecast until 2017.
According to the publication, the agency can lower the inflation estimate for 2015, which will eliminate the expected zero growth in incomes of the population.
The forecast assumed that the food sanctions of the Russian Federation are valid for a year - until August 2015.
How could such a high inflation be expected?
The current situation suggests a one-off shock, but the downward trend of inflation will not change," a source in the Ministry of Finance said.
Economists from VTB Capital do not share the expectations of the government’s financial and economic bloc regarding inflation and predict a price increase of 8% in 2014.
The main effect of food bans will come together with the possible introduction of a sales tax (VAT) in the regions of the Russian Federation in 2015, experts are convinced.
The inflation peak of 9% will be in February, after which the annual growth rate of prices will decline, experts believe.
By the way, last week Rosstat summed up the first inflationary results after the Russian Federation introduced “accurate sanctions”.
AIF.ru interviewed experts and found out their inflation expectations.
Artem Deev, Head of the Analytical Department of AForex FC:
Price increases are already observed in the main segments of goods.
Moreover, when socially important products began to rise in price, the government was forced to launch measures to systematically monitor price stability in order to prevent the risks of unreasonable price increases in the short term.
Suppliers and retailers are already reporting on a daily basis to regulators so that authorities know exactly who, when and for what reason initiates price increases.
The key drivers of the growth of the consumer price index continue to be the colossal pace of capital outflows, excessive refinancing of the banking sector by the Russian mega-regulator, internal conversion due to the flight of the population to foreign currency, as well as the embargo on imports of food products from countries that have joined the sanctions against Russia.
If inflationary pressures had remained under control, the cost of a basket of minimum sets of products would not have jumped 12% in a single quarter.
The ban on the importation of food products triggered a shock of supply on the domestic market and led to a perfectly logical increase in the final value.
Since at the current stage we are not able to fully launch the mechanism of import substitution, as well as to increase the self-sufficiency of the Russian market at the expense of domestic production, retaliatory sanctions will continue to bear the risks of growth of the inflationary component.
If we add to this the fiscal reasons related to the lack of confidence in the national currency, as well as the worsening prospects for economic growth, inflation may well exceed 8% by the end of this year.
Alexander Razuvaev, director of analytical department "Alpari"
In the 1990s, inflation sometimes reached 20-30% per month, in zero it was also higher than the current level, another thing is that then it was compensated by rapid economic growth.
I think by the end of the year, inflation will be 8-8.5%.
Platon Maguta, asset manager of the Maguta Foundation
The external factor associated with sanctions against Russia is still successfully contained, but if there is a further increase in pressure, primarily on the financial sector - it can lead to certain difficulties and increase inflation expectations of the population, which usually manifest themselves in the purchase of cash in order to secure their savings.
It can be assumed that the government, the Central Bank of the Russian Federation and the Ministry of Finance will try to mitigate the smooth weakening of the ruble, both by market methods and by state regulation.
But price increases start traditionally after the summer calm and may become more noticeable this fall.
The target level of consumer inflation in Russia of 7.5% is likely to stand, since Russia still has financial savings.
Gardening centers are saddened by the decrease in the number of homeowners
The drop, driven by an exceptional decline in the number of homeowners under the age of 35, could lead gardening centers to lose tens of millions of pounds a year when today’s young consumers reach “the primary age of gardening,” according to a study by HTA reported by the Financial Times.
According to this report, people renting homes spend an average of 55 percent of the amount that homeowners spend on gardening.
It mentions the increase in the number of people living in highly urbanized areas without gardens, the popularity of paving yards in front of a parking house, and the reduction in the size of the garden as other factors posing a threat to the industry, whose annual sales are estimated to be <0xC2><0xA3>5 billion.
In Greater London, where the number of homeowners has fallen from 61 percent to 43 percent in six years, the UK has the lowest level of spending on household goods for gardeners.
The HTA and the Royal Horticultural Society have reported that renting housing and the lack of space for a garden does not mean that people cannot grow plants.
Guy Barter, chief gardening adviser at RHS, said: “Cultivating plants in containers, for example, is especially popular with tenants who can carry plants with them when they move.”
