China's Biggest Companies Join Forces Against Alibaba
Chinese companies, including China's largest commercial real estate developer Dalian Wanda Group and Internet giants Tencent Holdings (social media, messenger, etc.) and Baidu (China's largest search engine), are creating a company that will compete in the online trading market with Alibaba.
However, catching up with the miracle of the Chinese Internet, which has left behind even its American rivals - eBay and Amazon.com, will not be easy.
the Union of the Largest
The companies plan to invest 5 billion yuan ($814 million) in the joint venture, 70% of which will be owned by Wanda and 15% of each of the Internet companies, the Wanda Group said in a statement.
Registration of the company is planned in Hong Kong.
The joint venture will combine Baidu’s search services with the popular social platform WeChat (the largest social network in China, with about 438 million users), Tencent and Wanda’s infrastructure.
In addition to a chain of 40 luxury hotels, Wanda manages at least 49 commercial properties across China and 40 shopping malls.
Last year, the company invested 50 billion yuan (more than $8 billion) in the construction of a movie studio and a theme park in Qindao, a city in eastern China on the Yellow Sea coast.
The project is expected to attract more than 1 million visitors annually and generate a profit of $ 960 million.
In addition, Wanda owns the American network of cinemas AMC Entertainment Holdings, which makes the company the largest operator of cinemas in the world.
By 2015, Wanda plans to equip all of its shopping malls, hotels and entertainment venues with e-commerce services, the development of which will be carried out by the newly created competitor Alibaba.
According to Dong Tse, who will lead the new company, thanks to the merger Wanda will be able to increase the number of users of its e-commerce services from the current 40 million people to 100 million by next year.
The new platform should become the world’s largest online-to-offline platform, notes Dong Tse.
The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract customers online so that they come to regular offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O is coupon sales services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the biggest cake in online commerce,” said Wanda Wang Jianlin, CEO of the company.
“Now there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation, everyone’s chances are roughly equal,” he said.
China’s e-commerce market is the world’s largest, and McKinsey & Co. estimates its volume will more than triple by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has risen to 632 million, according to Bloomberg data: this is more than the population of any country in the world, with the exception of India.
And according to forecasts, by 2015, this number could grow to 850 million people.
the Union of the Richest
Tencent CEO Ma Huaten was until recently the richest man in China, however, according to the Bloomberg Millionaire Index, Alibaba founder Jack Ma has already overtaken him by $5.5 billion.
Jack Ma’s fortune is estimated at $21.8 billion, of which $11 billion is his stake in Alibaba.
Baidu leader Robin Li is now ranked third among China’s wealthiest people, while Wang Jianlin of Wanda is ranked fourth.
“It’s very interesting to watch this battle: the three richest people join forces to challenge the even richer,” said Cao Lei, director of China’s e-commerce research center in Hangzhou.
But he believes that the new company is unlikely to seriously compete with Alibaba immediately after its creation: "Rome can not be built in one day."
The fact that it is not so easy to compete with Alibaba not only for new companies, but also for well-deserved leaders of the world of Internet trade, is evidenced by the report on the financial performance of Alibaba for the last quarter.
Alibaba is often described as something between eBay and Amazon.com, but between April and June, the Chinese company earned more than its two U.S. competitors combined.
Alibaba’s net profit for the period almost doubled that of its competitors – it almost tripled year-on-year to $1.99 billion.
“Alibaba still has a huge potential to generate money, largely thanks to its mobile apps,” said an analyst at Arete Research Service in Hong Kong.
According to the updated Alibaba prospectus on the website of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the number of active mobile users of the company's services in July amounted to 188 million, which is significantly higher than the March figure (163 million people).
At the same time, 32.8% of all Alibaba transactions in the past quarter were made on mobile devices.
Alibaba has to name the value of its shares before the IPO.
According to an average estimate of 11 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg, the company could be valued at $187 billion after the sale of shares.
According to Bloomberg sources, Alibaba’s debut on the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) may take place on September 16.
The road-show of the company, preceding this event, will start on September 3.
Alibaba’s IPO is expected to be a record in the history of the NYSE and will allow the company to raise about $ 20 billion.
So far, the record for the volume of funds raised on U.S. exchanges belonged to the payment system Visa, which in 2008 held the initial placement of its shares, earning $ 17.9 billion.
