The calculation of the estimates of construction projects in the Russian Federation will take place in a new way
Issues of pricing, regulation of the construction industry, as well as problems of connection to networks, the Federal Antimonopoly Service takes special control.
The FAS created an expert council for the development of competition in the construction sector.
At his meeting, Vadim Solovyov, head of the Department of Housing, Construction and Natural Resources Control of the FAS, said that "today's calculation of the estimates of construction projects is absolutely incomprehensible."
The regulatory framework makes pricing opaque and can lead to an unreasonable construction price, according to the FAS.
And they offer the cost of construction of state-owned objects at the design stage to determine on the basis of market prices of constructive solutions instead of the estimated norms and unit prices for technological operations used today.
These proposals have been included in the road map and are currently under consideration in the Ministry of Transport.
"Replacing traditional estimates in construction with calculations of structural elements should lead to less corruption in the industry," Solovyov said.
After all, now every bolt and nut is calculated in the estimate, and it is not always possible to check everything, so sometimes in the documentation, unscrupulous construction companies can bury "whole tractors".
In Minneapolis, I agree.
"The first developments on the transition to the calculation of the cost of structural elements already exist: methods have been developed for calculating prices for constructive solutions, drawing up estimates for these indicators," said Elena Zhukova, head of the Department of Urban Planning and Architecture of the Ministry of Construction.
The field of road construction was selected as a pilot.
However, experts believe that the problem is much more serious.
According to the head of the construction company "Profi-invest" Anatoly Demyanko, the estimated standards have long been outdated, but another mechanism has not yet been proposed to the business.
“As for the proposed calculations on the structural elements, in practice it is difficult to implement, because in the construction of buildings often used completely different technologies,” he said.
It is no secret that the construction market is developing largely thanks to the state order.
According to the Chairman of the Board of NP "Expert community of professionals of the state order" Ekaterina Lezina, today the state is the most solvent customer.
Vladimir Malakhov, Deputy Director of Engineering at the Rosatom Capital Construction Industry Center, drew attention to the fact that today the market is conditionally divided into companies that have access to a portfolio of contracts and companies that have monopoly competencies and do not allow competitors in this field.
He believes that the creation of a transparent market is possible only under the condition that access to contracts is maximally fenced off from someone’s controlling influence.
At the expert council, it was proposed to form a system of state orders in such a way that the same executor is not entitled to receive more than one contract worth more than 1 billion rubles or several contracts worth more than 1 billion rubles.
The Ministry believes that this approach should be evaluated in terms of the impact on business, as well as the effectiveness of construction management.
As explained by Elena Zhukova, in this case, it will be necessary to provide the customer with the functions of a general contractor, which will lead to an increase in the customer’s staff and budget costs for its maintenance.
At the same time, the customer’s specialists will need to have knowledge that allows to assess the quality of the works performed by the contractors, as well as their safety.
Often, such a breakdown will need to determine who will be responsible for the security of the facility as a whole.
In addition, this approach may result in the outflow of highly qualified participants in public procurement due to disinterest in receiving a state order for an incomplete amount of work and a small amount of contract.
The deputy head of the expert-consulting center of the Institute of Procurement Alexander Evstashenkov believes that now the state order procedure has turned into a business game for the attention of the contractor.
And gave an example: "the participant when filling out the application must specify "specific indicators" without specifying the words: "or equivalent", "must be", "from", "more", "less", "analogue", "or", "type", "similar type", "not lower", "below", "above", "may", "previously", "may not have", "previously", "previously", "may".
Thus, customers often abuse their right to set requirements for the content of the application submitted by the contractors.
Another problem 44-FZ, according to Evstashenkov, was the need to assess the quality of work through the participant's "paper" proposal at the application stage.
Considering the application of the participant, it is really possible to assess only the qualification of the contractor, but not the quality of the work, the implementation of which has not even begun, - the expert believes.
The quality of the work can be evaluated only when they are accepted.
The expert council also proposed moving margin income from the upper to the lower echelon to eliminate intermediate contractors.
The chairman of the expert council, state secretary, deputy head of the FAS Andrei Tsarikovsky believes that this should not be done, since the general contractor must be responsible for the order.
Otherwise, it will turn out, as in the famous repeat of Arkady Raykin's "Atelier": "Is there a claim to the buttons?".
Israeli children return to school after Gaza war
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip returned to school on Monday after spending the summer in bomb shelters as rockets and mines rained on their settlements during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed as the territory recovered from fighting.
The start of schooling brought a sense of joy and excitement to the missile-affected settlements of southern Israel, but the traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod, employees of the kindergarten "Pashosh", which hit the rocket, removed the traces of fragments from the walls and children's slides before the arrival of students.
“We’re a little scared, but happy to look to the future,” said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Saad and an English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really need to return to measured life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Bart, said it was "a bit strange" to start going to school again.
“It was a difficult time and we didn’t leave our homes at all,” she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited a kibbutz near the Gaza border to express his support.
Before the ceasefire halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border settlements such as Saad did not go out or leave their homes, moving to safer areas further from the Gaza Strip to escape rocket and mortar fire.
Many residents of Nahal Oz, a settlement near the Gaza border where a 4-year-old boy was killed by a Palestinian landmine, doubt whether they should go back.
The Ministry of Education said about a dozen families had not yet returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a city on the Gaza border that has been heavily damaged by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to study hard and said, "We will do everything we can to give you knowledge and ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite ceasefire on Tuesday.
The ceasefire agreement immediately put an end to hostilities, but key issues remained unresolved, such as Hamas’ demand for the lifting of the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and seaports in the Gaza Strip.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down its arms and return the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
A new phase of indirect talks is expected to begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, three-quarters of whom were civilians, and at least 494 children, according to estimates by the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes these figures and claims that at least half of those killed were militants; despite this, it has not provided substantial evidence to support this claim.
On the Israeli side, 66 soldiers and six civilians were killed, including one Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other Gaza militants fired 4,591 rockets and mines at Israeli cities, mostly in the south of the country.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, carried out more than 5,000 air and other attacks.
Israeli attacks have damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people have found shelter in more than 100 schools that have been converted into shelters.
With tens of thousands of people still in shelters and fighting continuing, education officials delayed the start of the school year last week.
"I hope that the school will open soon so that we can complete our education as children of the world and Jewish children," said Mohammad Amara, a 13-year-old boy who now lives in one of Gaza's schools.
