Production growth in the eurozone slowed to its lowest level in 13 months in August, according to a popular study.
The latest value of the Markit Business Activity Index (PMI) of the euro area manufacturing sector fell to 50.7 in August, falling from 51.8 in July.
A value above 50 indicates growth.
New orders have been delayed and businesses have suffered amid growing tensions between the EU and Russia over Ukraine.
The values came before the meeting of the European Central Bank (ECB) on Thursday.
Markets will expect a clear plan from the bank on how to cope with a halt to the recovery of the eurozone, as well as the threat of deflation with inflation of only 0.3%.
There is speculation that ECB chief Mario Draghi may give additional signals later this week that he is considering a quantitative easing scheme for the eurozone similar to those used by the UK and the US during the financial crisis.
“Although some growth is better than no growth at all, the inhibitory effect of growing economic and geopolitical uncertainty on producers is becoming more apparent,” said Rob Dobson, senior economist at Markit.
The PMI of Germany’s manufacturing sector, Russia’s largest trading partner in the EU, fell to its lowest level in 11 months of 51.4.
Meanwhile, in the bloc’s second-largest economy, France, the PMI fell to 46.9.
France continues to be a real concern, as is Italy’s weakening from steady growth to stagnation.
"Signs that the growth momentum has waned in the main industrial engine, Germany, as well as in Spain and the Netherlands, also do not add confidence," Dobson said.
A slowdown in industry is likely to fuel analysts awaiting additional monetary or fiscal stimulus.
One positive news was from Ireland, where the PMI rose to 57.3, its highest level since late 1999.
Howard Archer, chief economist at IHS Global Insight, said: “The best thing to say about the August survey of the Eurozone’s manufacturing sector business activity index is that it shows that the sector is still growing.”
He added: “The eurozone producers obviously find life very difficult at the moment, as the current heightened geopolitical tensions – especially those related to Russia/Ukraine – add to the uncertainty of the still difficult conditions in many countries.
This increased tension has obviously hit businesses — and especially consumer confidence — and is likely leading to some orders being delayed or even cancelled, especially large orders.
