X-ray results are here.
It was mesothelioma, an incurable cancer that affects the pleura, or lung shell.
For most cancers, it is difficult to determine the exact cause.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, for example, not all lung cancer patients smoked.
But with mesothelioma, it's different.
In almost all cases, the cause is contact with asbestos, a fibrous building material that was once called a “miracle,” but which is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma is a disease that we can ignore.
Asbestos, after all, is material from the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in the UK since the 1960s, when the recommended industrial ban came into force.
Even when it was in use, only people from specific industries worked closely with it: pipe insulators, builders, carpenters, and dock workers, for example.
An industrial toxin from another era, it is hardly seen as a cause for concern today.
But this calmness is wrong.
The UK is currently at the height of the mesothelioma epidemic.
More people are dying of mesothelioma here than in any other country on the planet.
With an annual death rate of about 2,500 people, more than twice as many people die from the disease as from car accidents.
Annual deaths from mesothelioma since 1980 and projected number of future deaths in the UK
The reason we feel its deadly effects now is that while the use of asbestos has been illegal for many years (all types of asbestos were eventually banned by law in 1999), it usually takes decades to develop mesothelioma.
And the attack of mesothelioma is not limited to veterans of the specialties of industrial construction.
Asbestos has been, and in many cases remains, planted in the homes where we live, the offices where we work, the schools where we study, and the shops where we shop.
As a result, mesothelioma does not pay attention to class, level of wealth, profession or age.
Bastions of choice, from fashionable London department stores to private schools, turned out to be no salvation.
The Parliament building is permeated with asbestos.
Even the hospitals that are designed to treat us have turned out to be reservoirs of this deadly carcinogen.
Andrew Lawson wasn't old.
He wasn't a pipe insulator.
