Car recycling program resumed on September 1
On September 1 in Russia resumes the operation of the program on the recycling of cars.
Until December 31, 2014, 10 billion rubles will be allocated for these purposes.
As the head of the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation Denis Manturov explained, the money is allocated from the limits that have already been brought to the Ministry of Industry and Trade of the Russian Federation through redistribution from other areas of support.
The program will apply to all vehicles older than six years.
The amount of compensation will be from 40 thousand for a passenger car to 350 thousand rubles for a truck.
Earlier in Russia, a similar program of recycling cars was already in place.
The main difference of the current project, the minister explained, is that now it is assumed not only the disposal of cars to receive a subsequent discount, but also the opportunity in the event that the car has reached the age of more than six years, to buy a new one with a discount when the old one is handed over to the "trade-in" from the dealer.
The previous federal recycling program, valid from January 1, 2010 to December 31, 2011, was spent more than 16 billion rubles.
Thanks to it, the level of production of passenger cars in 2010 amounted to about 1.2 million units (this is plus 101.4% compared to 2009).
The creator of Coming Out Simulator will release a game about modern journalism
Game designer Nikki Case, known for the game Coming Out Simulator decided to release a game about modern journalism.
He spoke about his project in an interview with Kill Screen.
Case started working on the game a few weeks ago, but this fact is widely known only now.
The game was inspired by events in Ferguson, where protests are taking place after a police officer killed an unarmed black teenager.
The focus of the project, which does not yet have a title, will be on how information coverage of stories affects their consequences.
The hero of the game, a citizen journalist, will need to photograph what is happening in areas where clashes between the police and the population take place.
The hero can take different pictures of what is happening, which will affect the course of events.
If he shoots the scene so that the police will look like heroes, and the protesters - bandits, the police will start to treat him better and let him go where the ordinary person can not go.
If he covers events differently, his photographs could turn peaceful protests into a large-scale riot.
Points in the game will need to be scored using the hero’s Twitter, in which new subscribers will appear if the photos posted there are popular.
The game does not have a name yet.
The release date and the platforms on which it will appear are unknown.
Case, however, posted an image showing how an event could change depending on how a photo of it was taken and processed.
In an interview with Kill Screen, Case explained that he had been thinking about the concept of such a game for a long time, but initially wanted to dedicate it not to protests in the United States, but to events in the Gaza Strip.
After he began collecting material for the game, the game designer realized that he lacked the knowledge and skills to cover the history of the region.
However, when he saw how the media covered the events in Ferguson, he decided to make the game based on what happened.
Nikki Case is an independent developer who releases browser games.
His most famous project was Coming Out Simulator, released in 2014.
This game, which tells about events from the biography of Case himself, is dedicated to how a bisexual teenager tries to tell about his relationship to homophobic parents.
