The army controls the new government of Thailand
General Prayuth (right) appointed Defense Minister Pravit Wongsuwan (left)
Thailand's military ruler and prime minister, General Prayut Chan-ocha, has announced a new cabinet in which more than a third of the posts are held by retired or generals.
Representatives of the army received key positions: Ministers of Defense, Finance, Foreign Affairs and Trade.
Prayut Chan-ocha was formally confirmed as prime minister on Monday after the King of Thailand formally approved the appointment of the head of the interim military government to the post.
The 60-year-old military, who seized power in a bloodless coup on May 22, was the only candidate for prime minister.
He was elected Prime Minister at a session of Parliament.
Earlier, the army appointed members of parliament.
According to Prayuth Chan-ocha, the coup was the only way to maintain stability.
It was preceded by six months of demonstrations during which protesters demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Yinglak Chynawat's government.
Prayut Chan-ocha will officially be the interim prime minister as the military plans to hold general elections in late 2015.
However, there are concerns that the military is trying to consolidate its power in the country.
The military came to power on May 22.
The paralysis of civil power.
The leaders of the main political parties were subjected to temporary arrest.
Immediately after the military came to power, they temporarily arrested leading politicians of the country, including Prime Minister Yinglyk Chynavat.
Some journalists and public figures were also detained.
The current political crisis has its roots in 2006, when the army removed from the post of Prime Minister brother Yinglyk Shinawatra Taksin.
Both of them are popular among the rural population, especially in the northern regions of the country, which has repeatedly ensured their success in the elections.
However, many members of the middle class and the metropolitan elite have entered the anti-government movement, which since November 2013 has virtually paralyzed the country.
