Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
The British woman said she had spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karin Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CHMT), a group of hereditary disorders that lead to nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK reported that misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are presumed to have BMD, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure gait, and squeezed toes.
Patients may experience numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that symptoms intensify over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (AF), a condition for which the prognosis was very poor.
Rogers thought she would be confined to a wheelchair by the time she was 18 and would die before she turned 30.
A mother of two, now 51, said: “I knew as a child that I couldn’t do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never roller skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot in school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into her medical records when her doctor left the room and it said she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I put my nose where it shouldn’t be, and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I went home, found information about this condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the worst panic possible.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I turned 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in that interval.
I went through it alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, “My dear, I don’t think you have this disease, because you would be in a wheelchair by now.”
I think you have something that's far less life threatening.
After several genetic examinations, she was found to have CMT.
“When he explained what SMT was, I thought I pulled out a lucky ticket,” she said.
The UK charity CMT announced a month of information about CMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The tax burden on entrepreneurs of the Washington zone increases as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and more jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country rose moderately last year as economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington area are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to the state and local treasury in fiscal 2013, 3.8 percent more than the $26.6 billion raised for 2012.
The tax burden on businesses by state and local level increased by 4.3 percent last year, to $671 billion, from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after consecutive years when accounts declined, in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes grew faster, 4.3 percent faster than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by professional services firm Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the county’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from entrepreneurial taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
The increase in tax revenues is largely driven by a return to the company’s previous real estate value, the researchers say, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 percent.
While a large proportion of these revenues come from large states such as California, New York and Texas, it seems the same thing is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, up $9.6 billion from 2012 — an increase of 4.2 percent from the previous year.
However, the observed return to real estate has no similar effect on the growth of state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one-fifth of the company’s tax bills.
Companies in Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of their state and local tax bills in the form of real estate taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that so much of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a nonprofit organization that doesn’t pay real estate taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Taxation Center.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
The income of entrepreneurs also seems to be improving, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the most in the region.
Although trends are oriented in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three localities.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the national average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average of 4.1 percent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of the three jurisdictions (each having the same corporate rate), equal to 6 percent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25%, while in the county it is relatively high - 9.975%.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year found that Virginia has lower taxes for state and local entrepreneurs and a generally more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is experiencing competitive pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina recently signed legislation to lower the corporate rate from 6.9 percent this year to 6 percent, the same as in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, the law could raise the income tax rate for entrepreneurs to as much as 3 percent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington area seem to be feeling better and thus paying more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Entrepreneurial taxes paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners – the transitional structure by which most small firms are structured – in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia rose by 20 percent last year to $2.4 billion, with a much faster rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
The researchers say the trend and increases in business tax revenue across the country are likely to continue this year, with revenues from turnover taxes in state and local governments rising 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington area may lag behind, as the decline in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
