The savings certificate will be named and irrevocable
The Treasury wants to ban bearer savings certificates, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of irrevocable deposit.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will prohibit savings certificates for the bearer.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as rates here are higher than on bank deposits.
The fact is that bearer savings certificates do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, since it is not necessary to make a deduction to the fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (DIA).
The piquancy of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken because of small and medium-sized banks that distribute such certificates, and it will affect Sberbank and the Bank of Moscow, which, according to the ASV, control 98% of the profile market.
Moreover, the share of the Bank of Moscow, according to the Agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, ASV explains, is that clients of a small bank that bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of its license, try to get money from ASV.
Some depositors, not having sufficient financial literacy and buying bearer savings certificates, may assume that their investments are insured.
The justified absence of insurance payments under these certificates in the case of revocation of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when holders of bearer certificates tried to recover insurance compensation through the court," the ASV said.
The problem, of course, is invented.
After all, no one will still pay buyers of certificates, since they by law do not have the right to compensation from the state.
If it were that the instrument is not insured in ASV, along with it would be banned and metal accounts, on which the funds of citizens are accounted for in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but no one is trying to exist yet.
The fact is, most likely, that bearer certificates are a very convenient security that can actually act as quasi-money.
At the same time, their movement is practically uncontrollable: any client of the bank can buy a certificate, transfer it to any citizen, and before cashing such a certificate can change many owners.
It is no coincidence that the bill stipulates that a savings certificate must necessarily be a nominal security, which must be stored in the depositary.
And to sweeten the pill banks, such certificates are allowed to issue without the right of early repayment.
That is, an analogue of the irrevocable deposit, which bankers have long dreamed of, is introduced.
