Putin grants Russian citizenship to Ukrainian pentathlon
Russian President Vladimir Putin has granted Russian citizenship to the famous Ukrainian athlete Anna Buryak.
The relevant decree is published on the Internet portal of legal information.
At the beginning of this year, the athlete moved to Russia for permanent residence and applied to the Federation of modern pentathlon with a request to give her the opportunity to play for the national team of the Russian Federation.
In 2013, she won two stages of the World Cup, won the silver medal of the European Championship in the personal championship and became the world champion in the mixed relay, which is one of the new types of program in this sport.
It holds the leading position in the current season.
According to the rules, in order to perform at the 2016 Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, she will need to obtain a special permission of the Olympic Committee of Ukraine.
Anna Buryak is not the first Ukrainian athlete to change her citizenship.
In July, Vladimir Putin decided to issue a Russian passport to chess player Ekaterina Lagno, a native of Lviv, who is a two-time champion of Europe (2005, 2008), the world of blitz (2010) and fast chess (2014).
As part of the women's team of Ukraine, the athlete became the winner of the Chess Olympiad in Turin (2006), the team world championship in Astana (2013) and the team European championship in Warsaw (2013).
SCR stopped the investigation of the crash of the Tu-204 in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (ICR) has terminated the criminal case on the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
Forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased speed of landing, the non-fulfillment of standard landing procedures by the crew, as well as the unintentional exit of the engines at increased speeds of direct thrust.
The Tu-204 of Red Wings, which followed the flight Prague-Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 while landing at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The aircraft rolled over the runway and caught fire.
The commander of the aircraft, a co-pilot and a flight engineer were killed at the scene.
Two flight attendants were taken to medical institutions, where they subsequently died from their injuries.
Three other flight attendants, hospitalized with severe bodily injuries, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, who was moving at the time of the accident on the Kiev highway, received serious bodily injuries.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
After the accident, the transport prosecutor’s office conducted an inspection at Red Wings, during which numerous violations were identified.
In February 2013, the airline's license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
