Anger proved to be the most universal and functional emotion of man.
An angry facial expression is biologically universal for humanity, and each organ and muscle group involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists from Australia and the United States found.
Their findings were reported in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and they can be read briefly in a press release from the University of California, Santa Barbara.
An angry expression of the face - displaced and lowered eyebrows, stretched in a thin line of lips, swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and it is made even by blind from birth children who have never seen it, says lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that this emotion arose for effective dispute resolution during conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the more opportunities he has to dictate his terms, and he communicates this to the interlocutor with the help of anger.
Researchers have found confirmation of another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and switch to handshake, consider themselves entitled to impose unfavorable conditions on others, and also prefer force methods of resolving conflicts to peaceful ones.
Starting from the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining,” the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create angry facial expressions should make the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor - and thus force him to agree to his terms as soon as possible to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled on a computer face where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or the chin extended forward separately did not make the face angry, the participants of the study unanimously recognized the person depicted with such physical traits as being stronger.
Human anger, like that of animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own power, forcing one to agree and obey.
A person inflates his nostrils and squeezes his lips with the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that displays its fangs.
Anger is “triggered” by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form that most effectively demonstrates to the opposite side the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of an angry person is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tooby.
The Ministry of Communications offered to allocate 250 million rubles to the TV and radio company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate in 2014 from the federal budget 250 million rubles autonomous non-profit organization "Teleradio company "Crimea".
This is stated in the draft decree of the government, prepared by the department, which was acquainted with "the tape.ru".
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating conditions for large-scale information coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space on the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the purchase of equipment".
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to re-equip the hardware-studio unit, video walls, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to acquire a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, from the allocated funds, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and the repair of the energy system.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget funds provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The state broadcasting company "Crimea" was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the TV signal coverage of the broadcasting company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Teleradio company "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
